<p>I have created a small dialog which explains my problem I want to bind the textbox Text property to a object attribute it works great in norma condition but it fails when the textbox is a modified control derived from original TextBox class</p>  <pre><code>import clr clr.AddReference("System.Windows.Forms") from System.Windows.Forms import *  class foo(object):     def __init__(self):          self.bar="bar_test"  class my_textbox(TextBox):     def __init__(self):         self.max_val=1e10         self.min_val=-1e10  class my_form(Form):     def __init__(self):         self.Width=50         self.Height=100          t_instance=my_textbox()         t_instance.Dock=DockStyle.Fill          self.foo_instance=foo()         bs = BindingSource()         bs.DataSource=self.foo_instance          t_instance.DataBindings.Add(Binding("Text",bs,"bar"))          self.Controls.Add(t_instance)  form_instance=my_form() Application.Run(form_instance) print form_instance.foo_instance.bar </code></pre>  <p>and I get the following output for the code</p>  <pre><code>  File "test.py", line 31, in &lt;module&gt;   File "test.py", line 27, in __init_   ValueError: Illegal characters in path </code></pre>  <p>I think that the new class cannot handle the binding  but then again how to correct this??</p>